04092nam a22005895i 9780520322615DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203226157 a10.1525/97805203226152doi  a(DE-B1597)570180  a(OCoLC)1198931012  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aN5310.5.E3 7aART0150102bisacsh04a709/.32qOCoLC220/eng/202302161 aDavis, Whitney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasking the Blow :bThe Scene of Representation in Late Prehistoric Egyptian Art /cWhitney Davis.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia studies in the history of art ;v3000tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tChronological Table -- tCHAPTER 1. History and the Scene of Representation -- tCHAPTER 2. Outside the Scene -- tCHAPTER 3. Circling the Scene -- tCHAPTER 4. Entering the Scene -- tCHAPTER 5. Failing to See on Contested Ground -- tCHAPTER 6. In the Morgue -- tCHAPTER 7. Looking Back -- tCHAPTER 8. About-Face -- tCHAPTER 9. In the Wild -- tAppendix: Pictorial Narrative -- tNotes -- tBibliographic Note -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe meaning of late prehistoric Egyptian images has until now been tantalizingly mysterious, as little understood as the circumstances of their production. As a result, analyses of these images have been general and often incorrectly illustrated. Whitney Davis now provides a welcome remedy in this detailed reinterpretation of the images carved on ivory knife handles and schist cosmetic palettes. These images are among the most important documents of early Egyptian history and include the Narmer Palette, often considered the very inception of ancient Egyptian image making. Davis deciphers the intriguing pictorial narratives and complex metaphors of images that are concerned with "masking the blow" of the ruler. "Masking the blow" refers to the ways that the images--from hunted animals to human antagonists--represent, elide, or suppress the depiction of a ruler's violent act of conquering an enemy. Examining late prehistoric Egyptian images in light of contemporary visual theory and illustrating his analyses with excellent reproductions, Davis goes beyond the usual concern for stylistic development and iconographic meanings that characterize prior studies. His work will greatly interest art historians, archaeologists, anthropologists, and students of the visual arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, EgyptianxThemes, motives. 0aArt, PrehistoriczEgyptxThemes, motives. 4aAncient Egypt. 4aEgyptology. 4ahistory of art. 4athe arts. 7aART / African.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520322615?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520322615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520322615/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles